{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:39:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:39:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12565"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12565"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.12,0.67,0.19,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5064"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63242"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42783"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a three month history of increasing shortness of breath. Her symptoms have now progressed to the extent that she finds it difficult to do her housework. She is no longer able to do any work on her garden as she finds it too physically exhausting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe New York Heart Association has a grading according to the severity of the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Using this system, which one of the following is the most approximate measure of her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Class I","Class II","Class III","Class IV","Class V"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass III \u003C/strong\u003E(marked limitation of physical activity) is the suitable classification for this patient as it correlates with her becoming breathless from less than ordinary activity (i.e. ADLs such as housework). They are comfortable only at rest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass I \u003C/strong\u003E(no limitation of physical activity) is not suitable as it describes patients who do not experience abnormal fatigue, palpitation or dyspnoea from ordinary activities. Note that healthy people will still be classified on the NYHA as class I!\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass II \u003C/strong\u003E(slight limitation of physical activity) is not suitable as it describes patients who experience fatigue, palpitation or dyspnoea from ordinary activities, e.g. shovelling soil, climbing two flights of stairs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass IV \u003C/strong\u003E(unable to carry out physical activity without discomfort) is not suitable as it describes patients who experience symptoms at rest, which are exacerbated by activity. The situation presented in the stem did not warrant such an extreme classification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass V \u003C/strong\u003Edoes not exist in the NYHA classification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["NYHA Class III describes patients who experience symptoms arising from less than normal activity."],"references":["Malik A, Brito D, 